05930nam a22008895i 9781501717109DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017036520  a97815017171097 a10.1515/97815017171092doi  a(DE-B1597)496479  a(OCoLC)998753828  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJZ1312 4aJZ1312 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a327.1/14090342231 aMacDonald, Paul K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTwilight of the Titans :bGreat Power Decline and Retrenchment /cJoseph M. Parent, Paul K. MacDonald. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b3 tables, 2 charts, 2 graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Desperate Times, Desperate Measures -- tChapter 2. Parry to Thrust -- tChapter 3. The Fates of Nations -- tStudies in Revival -- tChapter 4. A Hegemon Temporizes -- tChapter 5. A Hegemon Wakes Up -- tChapter 6. A Descending Whirligig -- tChapter 7. “Les Jeux Sont Faits” -- tChapter 8. Tsar Power -- tChapter 9. The Utopian Background -- tConclusion: Retrenchment as Reloading -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this bold new perspective on the United States–China power transition, Paul K. MacDonald and Joseph M. Parent examine all great power transitions since 1870. They find that declining and rising powers have strong incentives to moderate their behavior at moments when the hierarchy of great powers is shifting. How do great powers respond to decline? they ask. What options do great powers have to slow or reverse their descent?In Twilight of the Titans, MacDonald and Parent challenge claims that policymakers for great powers, unwilling to manage decline through moderation, will be pushed to extreme measures. Tough talk, intimidation, provocation, and preventive war, they write, are not the only alternatives to defeat. Surprisingly, retrenchment tends not to make declining states tempting prey for other states nor does it promote domestic dysfunction. What retrenchment does encourage is resurrection. Only states that retrench have recovered their former position.MacDonald and Parent show how declining states tend to behave, what policy options they have to choose from, how rising states respond to decline, and what conditions reward which strategies. Using case studies that include Great Britain in 1872 and 1908, Russia in 1888 and 1903, and France in 1893 and 1924, Twilight of the Titans offers clear evidence that declining powers have a wide array of options at their disposal and offers guidance on how to use the right tools at the right time. The result is a comprehensive rethinking of power transition and hegemonic war theories and a different approach to the policy problems that declining states face. What matters most, the authors write, is the strategic choices made by the great powers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGreat powers. 0aHegemony. 0aInternational relations. 0aRegression (Civilization) 0aRegression (Civilization). 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSecurity Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  arealist foreign policy, cutting the defense budget, decline and retrenchment.1 aParent, Joseph M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 English